class MinStack {
    private Stack<Integer> stack;
    private Stack<Integer> minStack;

    public MinStack() {
        stack = new Stack<>();
        minStack = new Stack<>();
    }

    public void push(int x) {
        stack.push(x);
        if (minStack.isEmpty() || x <= minStack.peek()) {
            minStack.push(x);
        }
    }

    public void pop() {
        if (stack.peek().equals(minStack.peek())) {
            minStack.pop();
        }
        stack.pop();
    }

    public int top() {
        return stack.peek();
    }

    public int getMin() {
        return minStack.peek();
    }
}
```

The `MinStack` class is implemented using two stacks: `stack` to store the elements and `minStack` to keep track of the minimum element at the top of the stack. The `push` operation adds the element to the `stack` and updates the `minStack` if the new element is smaller or equal to the current minimum. The `pop` operation removes the top element from both stacks if it is the minimum. The `top` operation returns the top element of the `stack`, and the `getMin` operation returns the top element of the `minStack`, which represents the minimum element in the stack. All operations are performed in constant time, ensuring efficient functionality of the `MinStack` class.

