```java
public int maxSumOfKSubarrays(int[] a, int k, int l, int m) {
    if (k * l > a.length || m > a.length - k * l) {
        return -1; // Not enough elements to form k non-overlapping subarrays of length l with the given constraints
    }

    int[] prefixSum = new int[a.length + 1];
    for (int i = 0; i < a.length; i++) {
        prefixSum[i + 1] = prefixSum[i] + a[i];
    }

    int maxSum = -1;

    for (int i = m; i <= a.length - k * l; i++) {
        int[] leftMaxSum = new int[a.length];
        int[] rightMaxSum = new int[a.length];

        int leftSum = 0;
        for (int j = i - 1; j >= i - l; j--) {
            leftSum += a[j];
        }

        leftMaxSum[i - 1] = leftSum;

        for (int j = i; j < a.length; j++) {
            leftSum = leftSum + a[j - l] - a[j - l - l];
            leftMaxSum[j] = Math.max(leftMaxSum[j - 1], leftSum);
        }

        int rightSum = 0;
        for (int j = i + k * l; j > i + k * l - l; j--) {
            rightSum += a[j - 1];
        }

        rightMaxSum[i + k * l - 1] = rightSum;

        for (int j = i + k * l - 2; j >= i; j--) {
            rightSum = rightSum + a[j] - a[j + l];
            rightMaxSum[j] = Math.max(rightMaxSum[j + 1], rightSum);
        }

        for (int j = i; j <= i + k * l - l; j++) {
            maxSum = Math.max(maxSum, leftMaxSum[j - 1] + rightMaxSum[j]);
        }
    }

    return maxSum;
}
```

The solution first checks if it's possible to form `k` non-overlapping subarrays of length `l` with the given constraints. Then, it calculates the prefix sum of the input array and iterates through possible starting indices of the first subarray. For each starting index, it calculates the maximum sum of non-overlapping subarrays of length `l` on the left and right sides, ensuring that the starting index of each subarray is at least `m` units apart. Finally, it returns the maximum sum found.

